            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Washington\u2019s story is woven from the diverse threads of the Bay Area. Raised in Oakland by his father, a proud Black union electrician, and his Filipina mother, a compassionate registered nurse, Kai grew up in a home where hard work and caring for others were core values. He was a bright, empathetic kid who saw the social inequities of his city firsthand and felt a pull to address them.\n\nHis path seemed clear when he enrolled in the Social Work program at San Francisco State University. Kai was energized by the academic frameworks for social justice, but in his sophomore year, the theoretical became devastatingly real. His younger sister\u2019s burgeoning struggle with opioid addiction fractured his family and his focus. Textbook theories felt hollow compared to the raw, desperate need he saw in his own home. Forced to help support his family emotionally and financially, Kai put his degree on hold, a decision that would redirect his life.\n\nNow 25, Kai channels that experience into his role as a Harm Reduction Specialist for a non-profit. His education became visceral; learned not in a lecture hall but in late-night phone calls, tense family meetings, and navigating a healthcare system that often felt hostile. He found his true calling in meeting people where they are, offering clean supplies, naloxone, and a moment of non-judgmental connection on the streets of San Francisco.\n\nHe lives in the Mission District with two roommates, his $62,000 salary stretching just enough to cover rent and essentials. His daily 2.8-mile commute on the 14 Mission bus is a rolling microcosm of the city he serves. His apartment is his sanctuary, filled with plants and books he rarely has time to read. His social life is small but deep, consisting of a few colleagues who understand the emotional toll of their work and his childhood friends who remind him of life outside of it.\n\nKai\u2019s dream isn\u2019t one of wealth, but of completion. He aspires to return to SF State and finish his degree, not just for the credential, but to merge his hard-won street-level expertise with the knowledge to effect systemic change. He envisions a future where his sister is thriving, and he is helping to build a more compassionate city, one conversation at a time."
