            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 19, searching for a misplaced textbook in his sister's room. Instead, in her small trash can, he found a piece of burnt tinfoil. The world tilted. All the theories from his social work classes felt like ash in his mouth. It wasn't an abstract \"opioid crisis\" anymore; it was the sharp, metallic smell of smoke in his family's home. That discovery wasn't an end, but a brutal beginning, rerouting his entire life toward the tangible reality of her pain and away from the classroom.\n\n2.\nHe remembers the first time he used naloxone, maybe six months into the job. The man was blue on a Tenderloin sidewalk. Kai\u2019s hands shook as he administered the nasal spray. The world held its breath for two agonizing minutes, and then, a ragged, sputtering gasp. The man\u2019s eyes fluttered open in confusion. In that moment, Kai felt a profound, terrifying clarity. He couldn\u2019t always save his sister, but he had just saved a stranger. This was his work. This was his purpose.\n\n3.\nHe must have been ten. A neighbor\u2019s kid fell off his bike, a bloody gash on his knee. Kai remembers his mother kneeling on the Oakland sidewalk, her voice calm and steady. She wasn't just \"mom\" then; she was a nurse, expertly cleaning the wound with supplies from her car, her touch both professional and infinitely gentle. He learned then that compassion wasn't just a feeling; it was an action. It was knowing what to do when someone was hurting, and doing it without hesitation.\n\n4.\nJust last fall, exhausted on the crowded 14 Mission bus, he watched an elderly Filipina woman quietly open her grocery bag. She handed a perfect orange to a young man who was clearly struggling, his hands trembling. The man mumbled a thank you and stared at the fruit like it was gold. No lecture, no judgment. Just a simple, human gesture on a lurching bus. It was a fleeting moment of grace that fortified Kai\u2019s soul, a reminder of the city\u2019s quiet, resilient compassion.\n\n5.\nIt was 2 AM last week, the weight of the day pressing down. He couldn\u2019t sleep, so he found himself on his phone, scrolling through the SF State course catalog for the Bachelor of Social Work program. He traced the lines of course descriptions with his thumb\u2014\"Social Welfare Policy,\" \"Community Organizing.\" It was a bittersweet ritual, a glimpse of the person he\u2019d intended to be. It fueled not regret, but a quiet promise to himself. The streets were his classroom now, but one day he\u2019d go back."
